        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will measure the CO lines and the continuum in one Science Goal. We will use 
two FDM spectral windows for the CO line observations. 13^CO and C^18O lines will 
be measured in a single baseband with the coarsest channel spacing of 976.6kHz 
(1.33km/s), because we are interested in the line flux, the line profile is less 
important. The 12^CO line will be observed in another FDM window with 
a channel spacing of 488.28kHz (0.63 km/s) enabling us to resolve the expected 6-8 km/s 
broad line into 10-13 channels. For the continuum observation, we define two 
TDM spectral windows, giving a 3.75 GHz total bandwidth. The line free regions of the 
FDM observations will also be added to the continuum data increasing the aggregate 
bandwidth to 6.56 GHz in total.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The data rate is high in this setup, but to fulfill our scientific aims we need to 
observe all three lines whose distances in frequency means that they can only be 
observed in two different basebands.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We expect a disk size of 7 arcsec for this object. In order to determine the location 
of large dust grains and study their radial distribution, the disk structure will be 
resolved in 12 beams across the major axis. For this purpose we request a spatial 
resolution of ~0.6 arcsec in our observation, thus, the C36-3 configuration would 
be ideal for us (we used this configuration to generate the simulation in Figure 
2, right). The maximum angular scale in this configuration is 10.9 arcsec, significantly 
larger than the expected disk size of 7 arcsec, meaning that flux loss due to the 
missing short spacings poses no major problem. Thus we do not request additional 
ACA observations in agreement with the suggestions of the Observing Tool.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To explore the dust structure of the disk and search for gas, we will 
observe HD 48370 at 1.3mm continuum and at the J=2-1 line of different 
CO isotopologues. In BAND6 the continuum and the selected CO lines can 
be measured in one Science Goal. Our sensitivity requirement is based 
on modelling the expected 1.3mm continuum image of the source. The total 
continuum flux of HD 48370 at this wavelength is 7 mJy (it is confirmed 
by our IRAM/NIKA observation at the same wavelength). Based on our 
simulations using the C36-3 configuration with a spatial resolution of ~0.6 
arcsec, we expect a minimum flux of 180 microJy per beam. In order to detect the 
dust continuum emission from our source with a signal-to-noise ratio better 
than 9 we request a continuum sensitivity of 20 microJy/beam. We note that to 
achieve the best signal-to-noise, we will combine the TDM observations with 
FDM data (using the line-free channels only) to compile the final continuum image 
(see also in Correlator Setup). To achieve the requested sensitivity we need 
46 minutes integration time (assuming an aggregated bandwidth of 6.56 GHz).
With this integration time and observational configuration for the CO lines 
we can detect 10^{-6} M_Earth CO gas (see Preparatory work in the Science 
Justification).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
