    <prp:abstract>The asteroidal belt and the Kuiper-belt, containing solid material from micrometer-sized dust grains to 1000km-size dwarf planets, constitute the Solar System's debris disk. Today this disk is very tenuous, but theory predicts that the original belt was significantly more massive and would have been amongst the dustiest of such systems at that time. Based on Herschel images, we have newly identified two 30 Myr-old G-type stars in the solar neighbourhood whose debris disks represent the highest mass end of the known debris disk population. Concerning their dust content, these disks can be considered as analogs of the hypothesized ancient Solar System debris disk. Here we propose to study these two sources with ALMA, obtaining high resolution millimeter continuum maps and CO (2-1) line observations. We will (1) study the spatial distribution of dust grains and parent planetesimals; (2) investigate the stirring mechanism in the disks; (3) look for signatures of planet-disk interactions; and (4) search for gas emission in the disks. The expected results will offer a glimpse into the ancient Solar System.</prp:abstract>
